This is a list of inventions by people who were born in [[Taiwan]] or current citizens of Taiwan.
==List== [[File:Bubble tea by Chill Bubble Tea.jpg|thumb|upright|Bubble tea]] *'''[[Bubble tea]]''' is a drink that contains flavored tea and tapioca pearls. It was invented in the early 1980s by Taiwanese street food vendors.<ref name="tea">{{cite book|last=Martin|first=Laura C.|title=Tea: The drink that changed the world|year=2007|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|location=Rutland|isbn=9780804837248|page=219}}</ref> Bubble tea vendors serve the beverage cold inside a translucent plastic cup with an oversized straw wide enough for the tapioca bubbles.<ref>{{cite book|last=Lovegren|first=Sylvia|title=The Oxford Encyclopedia of Food and Drink in America|year=2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-973496-2|page=223}}</ref> The drink is popular throughout Taiwan, Hong Kong, mainland China, Southeast Asia and the United States.<ref name="tea"/> *'''[[Connect6]]''' is a game similar to [[Gomoku]] invented by [[I-Chen Wu]], a computer science professor at [[National Chiao Tung University]]. The player who obtains six or more stones in a row wins.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wu|first1=I-Chen|last2=Huang|first2=Dei-Yen|title=A New Family of k-in-a-Row Games|journal=A New Family of k-in-a-Row Games|date=2006|volume=4250|pages=180–194|doi=10.1007/11922155_14}}</ref> *A universal '''[[crossed molecular beam]] apparatus''' for studying chemical reactions was developed by the Taiwanese chemist [[Yuan T. Lee]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lin|first1=M.C.|last2=Lin|first2=S.H.|last3=Neumark|first3=D.M.|title=Y.T. Lee Preface|journal=The Journal of Physical Chemistry A|date=4 September 1997|volume=101|issue=36|pages=6339–6340|url=http://pubs.acs.org/doi/pdf/10.1021/jp971954n|doi=10.1021/jp971954n}}</ref> In 1986, Lee was awarded the [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]] alongside [[Dudley R. Herschbach]] and [[John Polanyi]] "for their contributions to the dynamics of chemical elementary processes."<ref>{{cite web|title=The dynamics of chemical reactions - a fascinating new field of research|url=http://pubs.acs.org/doi/pdf/10.1021/jp971954n|website=Nobel Prizes|date=15 October 1986|publisher=Nobel Foundation}}</ref> *The '''integrated [[Video projector|laptop projector]]''' was first developed and showcased by [[Asus]], a Taiwanese computer manufacturer, in 2008. The built-in projector debuted at [[Computex Taipei]] 2008, an annual computer expo.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Herrman|first1=John|title=ASUS Laptop With Built-In Projector Raises PowerPoint Threat to "Critical"|url=https://gizmodo.com/5013328/asus-laptop-with-built-in-projector-raises-powerpoint-threat-to-critical|work=Gizmodo|date=5 June 2008}}</ref> Competitors such as [[Hewlett-Packard|HP]] in 2010 and [[Fujitsu]] in 2011 have since released similar products.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stevens|first1=Tim|title=HP launching tablets and notebooks with integrated pico projectors this year?|url=https://www.engadget.com/2010/01/21/hp-launching-tablets-and-notebooks-with-integrated-pico-projecto/|work=Engadget|date=21 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Robinson|first1=Mark|title=Fujitsu Notebook Ditches Optical Drive, Packs Pico Projector|url=https://www.wired.com/2011/04/fujitsu-notebook-ditches-optical-drive-packs-pico-projector/|work=Wired|date=22 April 2011}}</ref> *'''[[Instant noodles]]''' were invented by [[Momofuku Ando|Go Pek-Hok]], who later adopted the name Momofuku Ando when he immigrated from Taiwan to Japan. Ando created a method for deep-frying and drying noodles that could later be cooked using boiling water. He founded the [[Nissin Foods]] company, which in 1971 introduced instant noodles marketed as [[Cup Noodles]] that were packaged in Styrofoam cups.<ref>{{cite book|last=Laudan|first=Rachel|title=Cuisine and Empire: Cooking in World History|year=2013|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-95491-5|pages=310–311}}</ref> *The '''[[optimistic concurrency control]]''' method was first proposed by Taiwanese computer scientist [[H. T. Kung]] and American John T. Robinson in 1981.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kung|first1=H.T.|last2=Robinson|first2=John T.|title=On optimistic methods for concurrency control|journal=ACM Transactions on Database Systems|date=June 1981|volume=6|issue=2|doi=10.1145/319566.319567}}</ref> *'''[[Woodball]]''' is a sport invented by Weng Ming-hui and Kuang-chu Young in 1990. In the game, a mallet is used to pass a ball through a series of gates. The Olympic Council of Asia made the sport a program of the Asian Beach Games in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=MOFA honors inventor of woodball|date=6 July 2007|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2007/07/06/2003368273|work=Taipei Times}}</ref> The International Woodball Federation is based in Taipei, Taiwan.<ref>{{cite web|title=Historical innovation|url=http://iwbf-woodball.org/en/1-1.php|website=International Woodball Federation|publisher=International Woodball Federation}}</ref> *'''[[Xiaoluren]]''', the walking green man, is the animated traffic light system. *'''Floating gate transistor''': In 1967, [[Simon Sze|Simon Min Sze]] and [[Dawon Kahng]] invented the floating gate transistor, which provides the foundation for many forms of semiconductor memory devices.<ref>{{cite web|title=Taiwan flash memory inventor wins lifetime award|url=http://taiwantoday.tw/news.php?unit=10,23,45,10&post=20642|website=Taiwan Today|publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Republic of China (Taiwan)|accessdate=16 August 2017|language=en|date=25 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kahng|first1=D.|last2=Sze|first2=S. M.|title=A Floating Gate and Its Application to Memory Devices|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/j.1538-7305.1967.tb01738.x/abstract|website=Bell System Technical Journal|accessdate=1 April 2017|pages=1288–1295|language=en|doi=10.1002/j.1538-7305.1967.tb01738.x|date=8 July 1967|volume=46}}</ref> *'''Discovering HAART Cocktail Therapy''': Dr [[David Ho]] is a Taiwanese-American medical doctor and HIV/AIDS researcher who was born in Taiwan and has made many innovative state of the art scientific contributions to the understanding and technological treatment of HIV infection.
