[[File:Tortilla warmer.JPG|thumb|A plastic tortilla warmer]]
A round shaped container which helps keep [[tortillas]] warm during a meal.<ref>{{cite book | title=Viva Vegan!:200 Authentic and Fabulous Recipes for Latin Food Lovers | author = Terry Hope Romero | year= 2010 | publisher= Da Capo Press | volume =  | location= Philadelphia, Pennsylvania (USA) | isbn= 978-0-7382-1273-9 | page= 26 | url= https://books.google.com/books?id=CfS6iN2F0d0C&pg=PA26&dq=tortilla+warmer#v=onepage&q=tortilla%20warmer&f=false | accessdate = 20 January 2013 }}</ref> Warm tortillas are placed in the warmer, which is often lined with a cloth or paper napkin. Tortilla warmers made of [[terra cotta]],<ref>{{cite book | title= The Bread Bible | author = Beth Hensperger | year= 1999 | publisher= Chronicle Books | volume =  | location= San Francisco, California (USA) | isbn= 0-8118-4526-5 | page= 229 | url= https://books.google.com/books?id=dvwGDlfoB9oC&pg=PA229&dq=tortilla+warmer&hl=en&sa=X&ei=_VL8UPGXL8j9igLthYHIBA&ved=0CE8Q6AEwBDgK#v=onepage&q=tortilla%20warmer&f=false | accessdate = 20 January 2013 }}</ref> [[plastic]] and [[expanded polystyrene foam|styrofoam]]<ref>{{cite book | title=Rick Bayless's Mexican Kitchen| author= Richard Lane Bayless | year= 1996 | publisher= [[Charles Scribner's Sons|Scribner]] | volume =  | location= New York, NY (USA) | isbn= 0-684-80006-3 | page= 145 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JMxLEsZYF2sC&pg=PA145&dq=tortilla+warmer&hl=en&sa=X&ei=4VX8UNfwEumuiALe44HoBg&ved=0CGsQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=tortilla%20warmer&f=false | accessdate = 20 January 2013 }}</ref> are available and commonly used in [[Mexican cuisine|Mexican]] and Mexican-influenced cultures.

